<TEXT>
the president of the american psychiatric 
association is accused in a probate dispute of exploiting a woman 
who gave him 80000 a year in trusts and willed 5 million to a 
psychiatric institute she founded during a decade of psychoanalysis 
with him 
the legal battle is between dr george pollock one of chicagos 
leading psychoanalysts and francis l lederer ii only child of 
anne p lederer who died in 1984 at age 78 
pollock denies any wrongdoing 
mrs lederer left most of her estimated 5 million estate to a 
nonprofit institute she established four years earlier to promote 
psychiatric research and music none of the money has been paid 
however because her son is contesting her will in cook county 
probate court a trial is scheduled to begin july 5 
lederer accused pollock of improperly using his influence while 
treating his mother for depression to urge her to create the 
institute and wrongfully inducing her to bequeath her fortune 
to it according to court documents 
pollock who was attending the annual meeting of the association 
in montreal referred calls for comment to his attorney robert 
tepper of chicago tepper said he had advised pollock not to 
discuss the case 
but pollock denied the allegations in an affidavit dec 4 1986 
i never made false representations to her for the purpose and 
with the intent of improperly controlling dominating and 
misleading her and unduly influencing and wrongfully inducing her 
to execute her last will pollock said 
tepper said he saw no support or substantiation for claims 
that mrs lederer was incompetent or unduly influenced 
but anyone can file a lawsuit and these days it has become a 
recognized means of social expression he added 
dr larry strasburger a harvard medical school psychiatrist who 
reviewed pollocks conduct in mrs lederers case at the request of 
her sons attorneys contended in a deposition that there were 
grounds for a malpractice suit he was paid 200 an hour as an 
expert witness 
strasburger said he reviewed mrs lederers prescription records 
and found she was taking enough medication to become 
psychologically and physically addicted 
pollock who will step down as president when the associations 
annual meeting ends thursday also is director of the chicago 
