the attorneys contended that after mrs lederers husband a 
doctor died in 1973 dr pollock took the place of her husband 
and he constantly advised her on all facets of life from where she 
was going to live to what she was going to eat to what medical 
treatment to get to what raises to give the housekeeper 
tepper said mrs lederer and pollock were friends and that the 
psychiatrist accepted her financial gifts because there was no 
reason not to accept them a point of ethical debate 
but strasburger wrote his acceptance of large gifts to his 
family his institution and himself occurred in a pattern of 
conduct evidencing gross disregard for psychoanalytic principle and 
psychiatric propriety 
dr robert weinstock a psychiatrist and associate professor at 
the university of california at los angeles medical school said he 
knew of no specific guidelines on ethics that prohibit 
psychiatrists from accepting gifts or donations from patients 
i can say that it would be unusual while somebody is in 
treatment to accept large gifts he said in a telephone 
interview its not standard to do that 
the american psychiatric associations principles of medical 
ethics do not contain a specific provision against accepting money 
or other gifts from patients beyond professional fees 
but the principles do say a psychiatrist should not use the 
unique position of power afforded him by the psychotherapeutic 
situation to influence the patient in any way not directly relevant 
to the treatment goals 
