<TEXT>
danes on tuesday will be faced with 
the tricky choice between their nato allies and their longstanding 
opposition to nuclear weapons in one of the countrys most 
important elections since world war ii 
the sudden storm over denmarks role in the 16nation alliance 
came as a surprise to many voters usually more worried about 
unemployment and national debt than military issues a ban on 
nuclear weapons in peacetime has already been in effect for three 
decades 
the showdown began april 14 when the opposition led by the 
social democrats pushed through a parliamentary resolution 
requiring the government to notify visiting warships of the nuclear 
arms ban 
the united states and britain never confirm or deny the presence 
of nuclear weapons on their ships 
the allies reacted sharply saying the move jeopardized 
denmarks participation in the north atlantic treaty organization 
a meeting of natos nuclear planning group was rescheduled from 
denmark to belgium britain called off several royal navy port 
visits 
prime minister poul schlueter a nato supporter called a 
general election asking voters to take a stand on the issue 
has the danes national pride deteriorated so much that we 
will bow to pressure from abroad the leftleaning newspaper 
information asked in a frontpage editorial 
the question is the central one in the current debate and in 
that sense the election is the most important since the second 
world war 
it didnt help matters when reagan administration spokesman 
marlin fitzwater joked to reporters that danish means breakfast 
to me 
national radio played the englishlanguage tape on the air an 
unusual step and the liberal politiken newspaper printed the 
sarcastic headline reagan staff demonstrates its knowledge of 
denmark fitzwater later apologized 
the confrontation comes at a politically unstable time for this 
country of 51 million the last general election in september left 
schlueters fourparty coalition holding just 70 of the folketings 
179 votes but with enough support to command a majority on 
economic matters 
tuesdays vote is not a direct referendum on nato but a vote 
for representatives in the folketing what happens afterward 
depends on how many votes are split among the social democrats the 
biggest single party schlueters centerright coalition and a 
handful of smaller parties 
polls indicate that while most danes agree with the traditional 
antinuclear position many have contradictory feelings about nato 
one survey said 82 percent of those asked favored a nuclearfree 
zone in scandinavia and 46 percent said they would support the 
idea even if it meant denmarks expulsion from nato 
but a recent poll by the observa organization showed that 66 
percent of danes favor staying in nato and just 16 percent oppose 
membership the most lopsided margin in years 
another published survey showed that 46 percent of danes 
believed it was reasonable to ask nato ships to guarantee they 
carry no nuclear arms 36 percent did not and 18 percent were 
undecided 
denmarks lowlying peninsula and islands command the approaches 
to the baltic sea and nato strategists envision it as a key supply 
point in case of a soviet invasion 
the natodanish clash follows years of contention over denmarks 
declining defense spending which now amounts to 21 percent of its 
gross national product among the lowest in the alliance 
but in random interviews with window shoppers along stroeget a 
pedestrian street in the heart of copenhagen voters seemed more 
worried about domestic matters than global politics 
its not just a question about nuclear weapons but about the 
way the government runs society said susane nielsen a 
conservative voter who works in a health insurance office we 
have to face these economic problems 
unemployment is running at 97 percent with a national debt 
worth more than 43 billion the national bank has warned that 
denmarks currency could run into trouble unless costs are kept 
under control 
joergen thy editor and writer for a computer magazine said he 
planned to vote against the government because i dont think they 
have achieved much 
the nuclear question 
thats a joke thats not the issue something went wrong in 
the corridors he said 
the nonuclear notification letter the cause of the fuss has 
yet to be written its likely the note would simply restate 
national policy without requiring a response from the ships 
commanders 
defense setbacks are nothing new for the danish government the 
april 14 resolution was its 23rd loss in parliament since 1982 on a 
defense question it passed by 75 to 58 with 46 lawmakers absent 
but the timing of the resolution as the united states and 
soviet union discuss further cutbacks in nuclear weapons probably 
touched a nerve on the american side speculated nikolaj petersen 
a professor of political science at aarhus university 
when the usa reacts vigorously it could therefore be 
linked to the fact that denmark has contested an important american 
negotiating position he wrote in det fri aktuelt newspaper 
</TEXT>
