the weekend seizure of a 25 million yacht after 
less than onetenth of an ounce of marijuana was found on board is 
a headlinegrabbing scare tactic that violates common sense a 
civil libertarian said sunday 
but the us coast guards seizure of boats like the 133foot 
ark royal was meant to make an impact 
this new policy should be taken as fair warning to anyone who 
is using or transporting any detectable amount of drugs on our 
waterways transportation secretary jim burnley said when he 
announced the zero tolerance policy here two weeks ago 
but mary coombs a member of the miami chapter of the american 
civil liberties union said the policy sets a dangerous precedent 
to take somebodys property from them for something they 
probably couldnt control is excessive she said sunday 
the ark royal registered in delaware and operated only by a 
crew of six employees was boarded saturday in international waters 
in the yucatan channel between mexico and cuba neither its 
registered owner michael j rogerson described by the coast guard 
as the president and chief shareholder of tomima corp nor any 
passengers were on board said coast guard lt john felker 
a boarding party from the cutter tampa noticed a tiny bit of 
marijuana residue in a trash can during a friendly document check 
the resulting search revealed a little marijuana tucked in the 
dresser of a stateroom coast guard spokesman luis diaz said 
at this point the person who owned the contraband has not come 
forward felker said the crew will probably be released 
uncharged when they arrive at the key west coast guard station 
expected during the night he said the yacht was to be impounded 
we have been focusing all of our efforts in recent years on 
just the big smugglers but drugs are a twoway street diaz 
said this is the time were making the users pay it really has 
to hurt to see a luxury yacht taken away for what basically amounts 
to one joint 
asked if it didnt seem harsh to take away the boat under those 
circumstances felker said zero tolerance means exactly that 
without regards to the size of the vessel or of value of the 
vessel 
a usflagged vessel is us territory anywhere in the world 
we have authority to enforce us laws over that vessel anywhere in 
the world except in the territorial seas of a foreign state even 
then we may be granted authority by that foreign state felker 
said 
the reagan administration is stretching the law with its seizure 
policy said ms coombs 
congress may have passed a law that permits confiscation of 
property used in drug trafficking but thats not the same as 
saying congress had in mind that they would have a zero tolerance 
policy she said 
it violates a sense of proportionality ms coombs said 
its putting people at enormous risk with no very effective way 
of protecting themselves and as a civil libertarian i am troubled 
by that kind of policy 
my guess is the coast guard is going to fight pretty hard on 
this one she said its going to have enormous symbolic 
value 
the previously mostexpensive vessel confiscated under the 
program was a 300000 yacht seized off lake worth said diaz 
