under government pressure panamas 
banks prepared to allow customers to make limited withdrawals from 
their accounts monday for the first time in more than nine weeks 
a government order shut down banks on march 3 following a run on 
savings by panicky depositors and the imposition of us economic 
sanctions in an effort to force gen manuel antonio noriega to 
resign as commander of the defense forces 
the sanctions including the freezing of an estimated 50 
million of government funds in us accounts helped produce a 
severe cash shortage in panama which uses the us dollar as its 
currency 
after rejecting earlier government orders to resume operations 
with restrictions some financial institutions agreed to reopen on 
april 18 to accept deposits a week later the government allowed 
them to expand transactions but cash withdrawals were still barred 
meanwhile the government refused to allow panamanian lawyer 
rogelio cruz to reenter the country he had recently arranged bail 
for some members of the opposition national civic crusade 
cruz wife marcela de cruz said her husband was put on a plane 
leaving panama when he tried to return saturday from costa rica 
she said cruz was taken to a security office and told absolutely 
nothing before he was expelled 
some civic crusade leaders have been hiding for weeks after 
security forces raided their offices and homes 
several opposition leaders have been refused reentry or 
expelled during the 11monthlong political crisis and then allowed 
to return later 
panamanians unable to cash their paychecks have conducted 
business on a barter or cashonly basis since the closing of the 
banks public employees have received government checks in small 
denominations which they can use to buy groceries or pay utility 
bills 
supermarkets that take the checks use them to pay utility bills 
and taxes 
bankers and government officials agreed after a series of 
negotiations to resume limited withdrawals beginning monday 
some bankers said the compromise was little more than an attempt 
to produce the image of business as usual since the cash crisis has 
not eased 
the banks will be open but they will not be open said juan 
ramon felliu president of the industrialists union of panama 
rules issued by the governments national banking commission 
limit the amount panamanians will be able to withdraw from checking 
accounts to 25 percent of the balance on march 3 with a maximum of 
10000 money deposited after april 18 is to be free of 
restrictions 
withdrawals from savings accounts are to be limited to 50 
beginning a month after the reopening withdrawals of interest are 
unrestricted 
all withdrawals are subject to the availability of cash at the 
individual bank 
the governments caja de ahorro bank announced it would not cash 
checks for the time being the national bank of panama which 
normally honors government checks also said it would not pay out 
cash 
the panamana banking association which represents 93 of the 117 
banks most of them foreign previously insisted its members would 
not resume full services unless the government could assure an 
adequate supply of us dollars to back normal customer and 
commercial transactions 
