<TEXT>
in nine of the past 10 presidential 
elections the candidate who avoided discussing problems and 
offered an optimistic outlook was the winner according to 
researchers 
they say those results are being borne out this year because 
of the pack of presidential hopefuls who began the race democratic 
frontrunner michael dukakis and apparent republican nominee george 
bush offered the rosiest messages 
in analyzing nomination acceptance speeches of the two 
majorparty candidates since 1948 martin seligman and harold 
zullow psychologists at the university of pennsylvania found the 
candidate who avoided dwelling on national and personal problems 
and characterized troubles with an optimistic outlook ended up in 
the white house except in 1968 
that year hubert humphrey whose message rated slightly more 
upbeat than richard nixons came from behind in the polls to a 
narrow defeat on election day zullow said 
the danger is it tells a political candidate that if you shape 
statements to what they want to hear youll win an 
unscrupulous candidate can move further away from what he really 
means seligman said 
the correlation between the candidates ratings in the analysis 
and their actual margins of victory or defeat came almost as close 
as is possible in social science seligman said 
the researchers applied their theory to the 13 major candidates 
running at the beginning of the year for the democratic and 
republican nominations by analyzing texts of their speeches as 
published in the new york times in january and february 
the results of the study are due for publication in the american 
psychologist a psychology journal later this year 
the researchers counted the number of references to bad events 
or problems then had people who were unaware of the source of the 
sentences rate them for pessimism and optimism 
on the democratic side dukakis came in as the optimism winner 
followed by rep richard gephardt and jesse jackson bush was the 
winner for the republicans with former delaware gov pete du pont 
and sen bob dole behind him 
key to the high ratings for bush and dukakis zullow said was 
the low number of references to bad events but also a major factor 
in the equation was their tendency to view the problems 
optimistically citing forces outside the country or painting them 
as temporary troubles that would be overcome by a vote in their 
favor he said 
while jacksons campaign has been punctuated by a theme of hope 
his speeches frequently have focused on the problems of american 
society and politics zullow said 
dukakis tends to shy away more from discussing the countrys 
problems he said 
for instance a passage from a jackson speech about defense has 
him firmly blaming the reagan administration but using strong 
language in describing perceived troubles zullow said 
jackson said reagan put out the deal that we are weak 
militarily thats not true were the strongest military in the 
world 
but he adds our boys got killed in lebanonour boys are 
vulnerable in the persian gulf going up and down that river every 
day being looked at down the gun barrel of american made guns sold 
to the ayatollah illegally weve got a strong military and a weak 
commander in chief 
jackson loses points in the analysis by rekindling the trauma of 
the 241 marines and sailors killed by a car bomb in beirut and the 
current threat to the navy in the persian gulf 
bush like dukakis scored higher than the other party 
candidates by not dwelling on a problem and quickly looking to an 
optimistic future 
modern american voters seem to have a stable preference for 
candidates who are more hopeful zullow said 
